<paragraph id="8B8B36ACFFF4FFE1D285633308180D63" blockId="6.[151,1437,824,959]" pageId="6" pageNumber="169">
<emphasis id="B940EABEFFF4FFE1D28563330C6B0D46" bold="true" box="[151,282,825,851]" pageId="6" pageNumber="169">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation id="3B5C3CF1FFF4FFE1D332633208140D63" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3068364302" collectionCode="NHML, RAB" pageId="6" pageNumber="169" specimenCount="2" typeStatus="holotype">
The senior author has examined the 
<typeStatus id="548F880EFFF4FFE1D0A463320E690D47" box="[694,792,824,850]" pageId="6" pageNumber="169">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus id="548F880EFFF4FFE1D15C63330EC80D46" box="[846,953,825,851]" pageId="6" pageNumber="169">paratypes</typeStatus>
(
<collectionCode id="ED25AE69FFF4FFE1D1DA6333096F0D46" box="[968,1054,825,851]" country="Libya" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/49nc-28y0" name="Natural History Museum, Tripoli" pageId="6" pageNumber="169">NHML</collectionCode>
) and specimens in 
<collectionCode id="ED25AE69FFF4FFE1D6E6633308400D46" box="[1268,1329,825,851]" pageId="6" pageNumber="169">RAB</collectionCode>
. The species is easily distinguished by the strong, saddle-shaped impression of the elytral disc just before the declivity
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32E6527FFF4FFE1D2D5638A0D910DAA" pageId="6" pageNumber="169" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B8B36ACFFF4FFE1D2D5638A0D910DAA" blockId="6.[151,1437,824,959]" pageId="6" pageNumber="169">
<emphasis id="B940EABEFFF4FFE1D2D5638A0C280D8F" bold="true" box="[199,345,896,922]" pageId="6" pageNumber="169">Distribution</emphasis>
. The species is endemic to 
<collectingCountry id="F323763CFFF4FFE1D089638A0FB40D8F" box="[667,709,896,922]" name="Fiji" pageId="6" pageNumber="169">Fiji</collectingCountry>
, where it occurs only in the higher altitude rain forest (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA54B5DFFF4FFE1D751638A0DA20DAA" author="Roberts, H." pageId="6" pageNumber="169" pagination="251 - 272" refId="ref6423" refString="Roberts, H. (1977) Observations on the biology of some tropical rain forest Scolytidae (Coleoptera) from Fiji. II. Subfamily Ipinae - tribe Xyleborini. Journal of Natural History, 11, 251 - 272. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222937700770181" type="journal article" year="1977">Roberts 1977</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
